# PhD and PDRA Opportunities

Applications are invited for a **PhD** position and a **PDRA** position under a **Leverhulme-funded project** on **Active Self-Propelled Helices**.

The project will develop mathematical and computational models for electrically driven helical microswimmers in three-dimensional fluids, with a particular focus on propulsion, interactions, and collective behaviour. It will combine high-fidelity numerical simulations with analytical approaches to study how geometry, hydrodynamics, and externally applied electric fields influence particle dynamics. The work sits at the interface of fluid mechanics, active matter, scientific computing, and mathematical modelling.

The project builds on previous work on Quincke-rotation-driven active particles, including [D. Das and E. Lauga, *Active particles powered by Quincke rotation in a bulk fluid*, *Physical Review Letters* **122**, 194503 (2019)](https://journals.aps.org/prl/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevLett.122.194503).

## PhD position

The PhD project is suitable for candidates with a strong background in applied mathematics, fluid mechanics, scientific computing, physics, or a closely related area. An interest in mathematical modelling, asymptotic methods, partial differential equations, and numerical computation would be particularly valuable.

The student will work on analytical and computational approaches to problems in microscale fluid mechanics and active matter, including the modelling of propulsion and interactions of helical particles in viscous flows.

